{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_fireweed_ver01/data/sn86075096/00340581519/1958041501/0374.xml":{"full_text":"SURE CURE FOR\nWEED HEADACHES\n33\n\n.ft-:-*\nMi\nmm\nm\nm\n\n\ns f\n/Ivy r\nwm\n<Sf;>\n\n>/k\nm\n\u25a0yy.\n'\u25a0im\n>:>g\n\nM\nW\n4\n\n\n\nr\n\nO\n\nL\n\u00e9\na\u00df\nw\n7\nW\nW\nH IRM A IS\nAMINE\nESTERS\nBRUSH\nKILLER\n2,4-D 2,4,5-T\nA complete line of sprays and dusts for selective\ncontrol of broodleaved weeds in grain and grass\ncrops; also for killing trees and brush.\nCHLOREA\nCHLORAX \"40\nATLACIDE\nATLACIDE\u20142,4-D\nSODIUM\nCHLORATE\n\nA wide selection to kill weeds and grass in non\ncrop areas and to stop regrowth. Chlorea and\nChlorax \"40\" contain sodium chlorate combined with\nother proven chemicals.\nATLAS \"A\" METHOXONE IPC DUST SPRAY\nCIPC 4L CARBAGRAN lO CHIPMAN GENERAL\nAlso a Complete Line of\nINSECTICIDES FUNGICIDES SEED PROTECTANTS\nCHIPMAN\nfttther Informotion\nDistributor\nUi\nfor fred\u00ab<\u00bbs M\nContort\ni\u00ab Ye\u00ab State, er Write\nNearest\nCHEMICAL. COMPANY\nDep\u00bb. R,6200 N.W. St.Helens Rd., Portland,Ore.\nFOR CHIPMAN WEED KILLERS\nCONTACT YOUR NEAREST GENERAL MILLS ELEVATOR\nOr Write GENERAL MILLS, Inc., Distributor\nP.O. Box 111\u2014Great Falls, Montana\nWhen Writing to Advertisers, say\nI Saw It in\nMontana Farmer-Stockman\n18\u2014APRIL 15, 1958\nTouch With Washing ton\nKeeping in\n0\nA\n\u00bb\u00ab\u25a0Sb*\nMore Funds Budgeted\nTo Projects in West\nRecession\nWASHINGTON, D.C.\nfears are leading to actions that figure\nto have a major impact in the West,\nnext year if not this. The White House,\nin a race with Congress for public\napproval, has now taken these actions:\n1. Amended the budget for the\nnew fiscal year, starting on July 1,\nasking for almost $15 million In\nadditional funds for small-water\nshed work. The House committee\nin charge of farm appropriations\nhas not only agreed, but already\nraised the President's ante by $114\nmillion.\nThe watershed money goes for small\ndams and other structures to prevent\nfloods, and for land treatment meas\nures on farms.\n2. The President also has requested\n$46 million more than he previously\nasked for reclamation projects.\nThe money, said Interior Secretary\nFred Seaton, would be used in the next\nfiscal year \"for expediting construction\nnow under way.\nWestern lawmakers approve of the\nAdministration request for extra funds,\nbut also are calling for (a) an end\nto the Administration ban against \"new\nstarts,\" and (b) for additional recla\nmation spending before the new fiscal\nyear begins.\n99\nFARM BILLS OUT\nIt looks to be just about all over\non Capitol Hill except for the shout\ning. That, in effect, is how farm\nleaders here sum up the legislative\noutlook for the rest of this year.\nVeto of the support freeze bill has\ntaken the steam out of efforts to pass\nso-called omnibus (catch-all) legisla\ntion, Farm-area congressmen still talk\nabout it, but their hearts aren't in it.\nThey foresee almost certain veto of\na big bill. Piece-meal legislation, unless\nit is non-controversial, the lawmakers\nare convinced, won't get anywhere\neither. Reason: Inability of the Farm\nBloc to agree on individual commodity\nbills.\nThe Southern chairmen of both agri\nculture committees have come out\nstrongly against single commodity bills.\nSuch legislation, says Senator Allen\nEilender of Louisiana, the Senate A g\ncommittee head, \"cannot be passed.\n\"If we are to have a farm bill this\nyear,\" says House Ag. Chief Harold\nCooley, North Carolina, \"Congress must\ndeal with general legislation, embrac\ning the commodity-by-commodity pro\nposals.\nThe odds against one-commodity\naction were made pretty clear when\nCongress refused to send separate\ndairy legislation to the White House,\nalong with the general freeze bill.\nNO ACREAGE HISTORY\nLOSS FOR OVER-PLANTING\nIt is now final and official. Wheat\ngrowers who unwittingly exceeded\nacreage allotments won't have to\npay the market quota penalty on\ntheir '58 crop.\nIn addition, new legislation (HR\n11086), finally passed and signed, will\nprevent loss of acreage history due\nto over-planting of '58-crop wheat.\nAlong the same line is a provision that\nprevents loss of acreage history in '59\nand future years if the excess is de\n99\n99\nlivered to USD\u00c4, or stored to avoid\npenalty.\nThe wheat bill, as approved, also\nreaffirms the purpose of legislation\npassed last year: Namely, to prevent\nfurther buildup of wheat acreage in\nthe East at the expense of the com\nmercial wheat states.\nSIGNUP EXTENDED\nIf yon are on the ASC committee\nwaiting list** to put land in the\n'58 soil bank acreage reserve, you\nshould by now or very soon get a\nnotice that you may sign a contract\nif yon still want to. USDA an\nnounced bn April 1 that notices\nwould be sent out, and that farmers\nwere to have \"15 days from the\nmailing date of the notice to sign\nup.\nExtra funds voted for the soil bank\nare adequate\u00bb to take care of every\nbody on waiting lists, said USDA, ex\ncept possibly for some corn growers.\nEven in the case of corn, however,\nit looked as though most and perhaps\nall farmers on waiting lists could be\naccommodated.\nCould you get into the bank in case\nyou were not on a waiting list? The\nanswer was, maybe.\nIt would be possible, said USDA, in\nthe case of \"farmers who establish\nby certification that they made an\nattempt to participate in the program\n\u2014and if funds were available.\n\nPARITY INCREASE\nDairy price support In the new\nmarketing year that started on\nApril 1 is a bit higher than the\ndollar-cents level originally an\nnounced. Due to an increase in\nparity, the final rates are $5.06 for\nfactory milk instead of $3.03 and\n56.6 cents for butterfat instead of\n56.2 cents.\nCorn support for '58, meantime, has\nbeen announced by Secretary Benson,\nsubject to a possible increase (but no\nreduction) before the start of th\u00e9 mar\nketing year on Oct. 1. The new support\nrate was placed at $1.36 per bushel\ncompared with $1.40 for '57-crop corn.\nPercentage support in '58 will be\n75 per cent, the same as for the 1957\ncrop. The dollar-cents drop is due to a\ndecline in parity.\nWhether non-compliance corn from\nthe new crop will be supported. Secre\ntary Benson had not indicated as we\nwent to press. Non-compliance corn\nfrom the 1957 crop has been propped\nat $1.10 a bushel.\nFOOD SALES HIGH\nHow deep is the recession?\nOne measure is the number of\npeople out of jobs, compared with\nthe size of the total labor force.\nIn 1933, at the depth of the great\ndepression, economists point out.\nJust about 25 per cent of our citi\nzens were out of work. Or, to put\nit another way, one in four people\nwho normally held jobs did not\nhave one.\nThe comparable percentage today,\ngovernment figures show, is about 10\nper cent.\nTo date, the recession has had no\napparent impact upon demand for food.\nIn fact, the latest official report\nshowed that food sales over the country\nwere 8 per cent above a year earlier.\nConsumer income has gone down about\n1 per cent since the recession started.","height":"20292","width":"15672"}}
